d bacteria to cope with stress. Focusing on the ecology of key organisms, each chapter is relevant to wetland regulation and assessment, wetland restoration, how flood pulses control the ecology of most wetland complexes, and how human regulation of flood pulses threatens wetland biotic integrity. Ideal for the classroom, this book is a fundamental resource for anyone interested in the current state of our wetlands.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aWetland ecology. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh1 aBatzer, Darold P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSharitz, Rebecca R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932890423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520932890.jpg  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles